Rust

Raylib

Cargo

Cargo is the package manager and also a build system for rust, it works as cmake does, but in a truly fashionable way.

list cargo commands:

  • ==cargo build== ‚Üí ./target/debug/$binary$
  • ==cargo run== ‚Üí build and runs automatically
  • ==cargo new== project_name ‚Üí use --help to see details
  • ==cargo check== ‚Üí does not create an binary file, just check its possible failures.
  • ==cargo build== ==--release== ‚Üí create a /target/realese/binary with some optimizations.

Imports

use std::io is the standard lib, just as C.

but you can use different ones by adding those to cargo.toml and importing it following this structure :

use std::io;
use rand::Rng;
use std::io::{Write, BufReader, BufRead, ErrorKind};
use std::fs::File;
use std::cmp::Ordering;

User input example

io::stdin().read_line(&mut guess).expect("Failed to read line");

This code uses input/output standard method stdin to get user input. The read_line function reads the line üëç and insert it by a referenced version of the guess variable, defined before. If an error occurs, it is handled by expect function, which returns the String you inserted there.

This is divided in the Ok and Err variants from Result type, handled separately.

Crates

A crate is a collection of Rust source code files. The rand
crate is a
library crate, which contains code that is intended to be used in other programs and can‚Äôt be executed on its own.

add deps to cargo.toml

// [...]
[dependencies]
rand = "0.8.5"

Crates.io is where people in the Rust ecosystem post their open source Rust projects for others to use.

Declarations

  • fn - function creation word
  • fn main () - main

Variables

  • let - defined word for creating a variable.
  • let &mut - the only one which is actually mutable
  • const - constant

Numbers

// float: f8, f16, f32, f64, f128, fsize

Operators

same as in C, +, -, /, *, %, ‚Äòop‚Äô= ‚Ä¶

random numbers

let something: i32= rand::thread_rng().gen_range(1..=100);

This code generates a random number from 1 to 99 using thread_rng method. In this case, we are using gen_range set as 1..=100 .

Conditional

  • if, else if and else like normal
  • ternary:
let my_age: i32 = 47;
    let can_vote: bool = if my_age >= 18{
        true
    } else {
        false
    };
    
    println!("Can Vote: {}", can_vote);
  • match
let age2: i32 = 8;
    match age2 {
        1..=18 => println!("Important"),
        21 | 50 => println!("Important"),
        65..=i32::MAX => println!("Not Important"),
        _ => println!("Not Important"),
    };
  • match with .cmp
use std::cmp::Ordering;
match guess.cmp(&secret_number) {
        Ordering::Less => println!("Too small!"),
        Ordering::Greater => println!("Too big!"),
        Ordering::Equal => println!("You win!"),
    }
